nce"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you want to continue to use and learn about GAMs, here are a number of other resources:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"ul","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://github.com/noamross/gam-resources/blob/master/2017-11-14-noamross-gams-nyhackr.pdf"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Slides"}]},{"type":"text","value":" and "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q4_t8jXcQgc"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Video (~80 minutes)"}]},{"type":"text","value":" from my talk at the "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://www.meetup.com/nyhackr/"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"New York Open Statistical Meetup"}]},{"type":"text","value":" provide a high-level introduction of many things that GAMs and "},{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"mgcv"}]},{"type":"text","value":" can do."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Materials from a "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://noamross.github.io/mgcv-esa-2018/"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"2018 Ecological Society of America workshop on GAMs"}]},{"type":"text","value":", by Eric Pedersen, David L. Miller, Gavin Simpson, and myself.  These are designed for an interactive workshop but may still be useful for self-teaching. The target audience for these materials is graduate students with a some statistical training; knowledge of GLMs is a prerequisite. There is more material on statistical inference, theory and the more exotic outcome distributions. See the "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://noamross.github.io/mgcv-esa-2018/links_and_bibliography.html"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"references page"}]},{"type":"text","value":" in particular for papers from the statistical literature."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The essential GAMs reference is Simon Wood’s "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://www.crcpress.com/Generalized-Additive-Models-An-Introduction-with-R-Second-Edition/Wood/p/book/9781498728331"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Generalized Additive Models in R"}]},{"type":"text","value":".  "}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://m-clark.github.io/generalized-additive-models/"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"An online book"}]},{"type":"text","value":" by Michael Clark gives a very nice short introduction to both GAM theory and use in R if you want an alternative approach from this course."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"On, Gavin Simpsons’ excellent, "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://www.fromthebottomoftheheap.net/"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"GAM-centric blog"}]},{"type":"text","value":", he tries out new and little-used GAM formulations."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"li","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/mgcv"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"StackOverflow"}]},{"type":"text","value":" and "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/tagged/mgcv"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Cross Validated"}]},{"type":"text","value":" have tags for "},{"type":"element","tagNam